🐍 Snaky Strings
📌 Problem Statement

Chef calls a string snaky if it either starts or ends with the letter 's'.

You are given a string A of length 4, consisting only of lowercase English letters.
Determine whether the string is snaky or not.

📥 Input Format
A single line containing a string A of length 4.
📤 Output Format
Print "Yes" if the string is snaky.
Otherwise, print "No".

✅ Output is case-insensitive:
Yes, YES, yes, yEs are all accepted.

⚙️ Constraints
Length of A = 4
Each character is a lowercase English letter (a to z)
🧠 Logic

A string is considered snaky if:

The first character is 's'
OR
The last character is 's'
🧪 Examples
Example 1

Input

hiss

Output

Yes

Explanation
The string ends with 's', so it is snaky.

Example 2

Input

rock

Output

No

Explanation
The string neither starts nor ends with 's'.

Example 3

Input

snow

Output

Yes

Explanation
The string starts with 's'.

💻 Java Solution
import java.util.*;

class Codechef
{
    public static void main (String[] args) throws java.lang.Exception
    {
        Scanner s = new Scanner(System.in);
        String str = s.nextLine();

        if (str.startsWith("s") || str.endsWith("s")) {
            System.out.println("Yes");
        } else {
            System.out.println("No");
        }
    }
}
🚀 Alternative Approach

Using character indexing:

if (str.charAt(0) == 's' || str.charAt(3) == 's')
📊 Complexity
Time Complexity: O(1)
Space Complexity: O(1)
🙌 Summary
Check first and last characters
If either is 's', print "Yes"
Otherwise, print "No"
